    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i keep getting confused with ac circuits. can u explain the difference between resistance and reactance? like why do i need both for impedance? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Resistance is the opposition to alternating current caused by the actual energy dissipation, like in a resistor, and it's always in phase with voltage. Reactance, on the other hand, is the opposition caused by capacitors or inductors, which stores and releases energy. Impedance is the total opposition to AC current, which is the combination, or vector sum, of both the resistive and reactive components. You need both because in AC circuits, energy can be dissipated (resistance) or temporarily stored/released (reactance).",
      "source": "target",
