      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so if i have a circuit with a 50 ohm resistor and an inductor that has 120 ohms of inductive reactance, how do i actually calculate the total impedance? do i just add them together or is there a different way to do it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Since resistance and inductive reactance are $90^\\circ$ out of phase, you cannot simply add them directly like scalar quantities. Instead, you must use the Pythagorean theorem to find the total impedance ($Z$). The formula is $Z = \\sqrt{R^2 + X_L^2}$, where $R$ is resistance and $X_L$ is inductive reactance. Plugging in your values, $Z = \\sqrt{50^2 + 120^2}$, which results in an impedance of 130 ohms.",
      "source": "target",
