    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so the phase shift is what makes it tricky. what happens if the circuit has both an inductor and a capacitor? does the reactance just cancel out or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you have both an inductor ($X_L$) and a capacitor ($X_C$), the reactances oppose each other because they cause phase shifts in opposite directions. The total net reactance is found by subtracting the smaller value from the larger one: $X_{\\text{net}} = |X_L - X_C|$. You then calculate the total impedance using the same Pythagorean theorem: $Z = \\sqrt{R^2 + (X_L - X_C)^2}$. This phenomenon, where opposing reactances cancel, is called resonance.",
      "source": "target",
